      "description": "<link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"https://instructure-uploads-pdx.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/account_152790000000000001/attachments/19401206/dp_app.css\"><p>There are four separate tasks listed below.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Task 1: Complete Orientation Survey &amp; Join the Slack Workspace</h3>\n<p>If you haven't done so, please complete the <a title=\"Orientation Survey\" href=\"https://canvas.calpoly.edu/courses/177412/quizzes/307575\" data-course-type=\"quizzes\" data-published=\"true\" data-api-endpoint=\"https://canvas.calpoly.edu/api/v1/courses/177412/quizzes/307575\" data-api-returntype=\"Quiz\">Orientation Survey</a>.</p>\n<p>The link to the Slack workspace for this class is on the Home page, under \"Instructional Information\".</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Task 2: Setting Up Environment</h3>\n<p>You are encouraged to use the department Linux machines (lab machines or servers) for some of the assignments in this course. The servers can be accessed (through the <a class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://tech.calpoly.edu/services/vpn\" target=\"_blank\">vpn</a> if off campus) by connecting, via ssh, to one of <code>unix1.csc.calpoly.edu </code> (for primary use), <code>unix2.csc.calpoly.edu</code>, and <code>unix3.csc.calpoly.edu</code>.</p>\n<p>If you are connecting to a department server from your machine, then was your password requested? If so, then you are encouraged to configure <a class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/how-to-configure-ssh-key-based-authentication-on-a-linux-server\" target=\"_blank\">key authentication</a>. If you are presently working in lab on one of the machines, then you are encouraged to configure key authentication from your personal machine at another time.</p>\n<p>We are also going to be using GitHub in this course for sharing code (me sharing starter code with you all and you all sharing your completed code with me).</p>\n<p>For this task, f<span>ollow the following directions: <a title=\"Setting up remote connection and Git through terminal\" href=\"https://canvas.calpoly.edu/courses/177412/pages/setting-up-remote-connection-and-git-through-terminal\" data-course-type=\"wikiPages\" data-published=\"true\" data-api-endpoint=\"https://canvas.calpoly.edu/api/v1/courses/177412/pages/setting-up-remote-connection-and-git-through-terminal\" data-api-returntype=\"Page\">Setting up remote connection and Git through terminal</a></span></p>\n<p><span>***NOTE***: The directions assume you have a unix-based machine. If you're on Windows, I recommend installing a free SSH client or free enhanced terminal, such as:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span>MobaXterm (<a href=\"https://mobaxterm.mobatek.net/\" target=\"_blank\">https://mobaxterm.mobatek.net/</a></span><span>)</span></li>\n<li><span>Terminus (<a href=\"https://termius.com/free-ssh-client-for-windows\" target=\"_blank\">https://termius.com/free-ssh-client-for-windows</a></span><span>)</span></li>\n<li><span>PuTTy (<a href=\"https://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/putty/latest.html\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/putty/latest.html</a></span><span>)</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><span>Task 3: The Importance of Security in Distributed Systems<br></span></h3>\n<p>The following is a cool, yet scary video about a distributed systems we use every day and a vulnerability that makes us all susceptible to potentially devastating attacks.</p>\n<p><a class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wVyu7NB7W6Y\" target=\"_blank\">Exposing The Flaw In Our Phone System</a></p>\n<p>This video highlights why security, particularly in distributed systems, needs to be \"built in, not bolted on\". Watch this video and write a short paragraph sharing your thoughts (Was it interesting or boring? What did you learn? Did it change how you think about your phone's security?). Your paragraph should also include your thoughts on why you think security in distributed systems is often treated as an afterthought instead of being built into the design from the start?</p>\n<p>To submit your paragraph, put it in the \"thoughts.txt\" file that you created in the previous task and commit it to your repo.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><span>Task 4: Getting Started on the Term Survey Paper</span></h3>\n<p><span>The term survey paper assignment instructions can be found here: <a title=\"Term Survey Paper\" href=\"https://canvas.calpoly.edu/courses/177412/assignments/1479180\" data-course-type=\"assignments\" data-published=\"true\" data-api-endpoint=\"https://canvas.calpoly.edu/api/v1/courses/177412/assignments/1479180\" data-api-returntype=\"Assignment\">Term Survey Paper</a></span></p>\n<p>To get started on your paper, first form your group. You are allowed to be in a group of no more than 3 total people. Use the following spreadsheet (which will become available after the course roster is finalized) to indicate your groups and topics: <span style=\"color: #0e68b3;\">Link not available yet</span></p>\n<p>Next, choose the topic you want to survey. To figure out what topic you are interested in, look through the proceedings of leading conferences and journals related to networking, distributed systems, and parallel computing. Below are a list of conferences and journals to look into:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>ACM SIGCOMM (ACM Special Interest Group on Data Communication)</li>\n<li>USENIX NSDI (USENIX Symposium on Networked Systems Design and Implementation)</li>\n<li>IEEE ICDCS (IEEE International Conference on Distributed Computing Systems)</li>\n<li>IEEE INFOCOM (IEEE Conference on Computer Communications)</li>\n<li>IEEE S&amp;P (IEEE Symposium on Security and Privacy)</li>\n<li>USENIX Security</li>\n<li>ACM CCS (ACM Conference on Computer and Communications Security)</li>\n<li>SC (The International Conference for High Performance Computing, Networking, Storage, and Analysis)</li>\n<li>ICPP (The International Conference on Parallel Processing)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Your topic should not be too broad (e.g., \"network security\" would be too broad, but \"DDoS defense\" would be more appropriate), but it should not be too specific so that you cannot find enough papers to write your paper on.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>For this task, you do not have to turn anything in, but it will help you get started on your proposal, which is due very soon.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Submitting</h3>\n<p>Push and commit all relevant files to your PRIVATE repository (make sure to add me as a collaborator, along with all of the ISAs - their emails can be found on the front page) and submit the URL of your private repo.</p><script src=\"https://instructure-uploads-pdx.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/account_152790000000000001/attachments/19401205/dp_app.js\"></script>",
